In article <C9v409.CC4@news.cso.uiuc.edu> mitchell@mehlville.ncsa.uiuc.edu (myself) writes:

>You can access the RSA primaries and use them, but it violates the license.
>So much for writing a legal version of PGP using RSAREF hooks.  The
>license pretty much limits you to implementing RIPEM, which uses the
>flawed DES.  Oh well...

This cannot be true. RSADSI says one can ask permission to go beyond the
interface. Apparently it was granted at least to RIPEM and MacRIPEM, which
use RSAREF and Triple DES.

